{"title_page": "John Patrick Micklethwait Brenan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n'''John Patrick Micklethwait Brenan''' was a British [[botanist]]. He was born on 19 June 1917 in [[Chislehurst]]<ref name=\"Kew Bulletin\">{{cite journal | title=John Patrick Micklethwait Brenan (1917\u20131985) | author=Verdcourt, Bernard | journal=[[Kew Bulletin]] | year=1987 | volume=42 | issue=2 | pages=286\u2013296|jstor = 4109685}}</ref> (which is now in the [[London Borough of Bromley]]) and died on 26 September 1985<ref name=\"Kew Bulletin\"/> at [[Kew]]. He is buried at [[St. Anne's Church, Kew]].\n\nBrenan received his [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge)|Master of Arts]] in Biology from the [[University of Oxford]] in 1940 and began to work at the [[Imperial Forestry Institute]] (now the [[Oxford Forestry Institute]])<ref>[http://www.plants.ox.ac.uk/ofi/ Oxford Forestry Institute<!-- bot-generated title -->] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302170136/http://www.plants.ox.ac.uk/ofi/ |date=2 March 2015 }} at www.plants.ox.ac.uk</ref> in [[Oxford]]. He collected plants from 1947 to 1948 in what is today [[Zambia]] and [[Tanzania]].\n\nHe began work at the [[herbarium]] of the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] in 1948 and became head of its African section in 1959. He became a member of the [[Linnean Society of London]] in 1952. In 1965, he became head of the herbarium and assistant director and became director of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew in 1976. He was a member of several [[learned society|learned societies]], and was president of the [[Association of Tropical Botany]] from 1970 to 1971, and of the [[Botanical Society of the British Isles]] in 1982. This botanist is denoted by the [[List of botanists by author abbreviation|author abbreviation]] '''<span class=\"vcard\"><span class=\"fn n\"><span class=\"nickname\">Brenan</span></span></span>''' when [[Author citation (botany)|citing]] a [[botanical name]].<ref>{{cite book|last = Brummitt|first = R. K.|author2=Powell, C. E.|title = Authors of Plant Names |publisher = [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] |year = 1992 |isbn = 978-1-84246-085-6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Ray Desmond (1994). ''Dictionary of British and Irish Botanists and Horticulturists including Plant Collectors, Flower Painters and Garden Designers''. Taylor & Francis and the [[Natural History Museum, London]]. {{ISBN|0-85066-843-3}}\n\n{{Directors of Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brenan, John Patrick Micklethwait}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British botanists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in Kew Gardens]]\n[[Category:Botanists with author abbreviations]]\n[[Category:Burials at St. Anne's Church, Kew]]\n[[Category:English botanists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:People from Chislehurst]]\n\n{{UK-botanist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n'''John Patrick Micklethwait Brenan''' was a British [[botanist]]. He was born on 19 June 1917 in [[Chislehurst]]<ref name=\"Kew Bulletin\">{{cite journal | title=John Patrick Micklethwait Brenan (1917\u20131985) | author=Verdcourt, Bernard | journal=[[Kew Bulletin]] | year=1987 | volume=42 | issue=2 | pages=286\u2013296|jstor = 4109685}}</ref> (which is now in the [[London Borough of Bromley]]) and died on 26 September 1985<ref name=\"Kew Bulletin\"/> at [[Kew]]. He is buried at [[St. Anne's Church, Kew]].\n\nBrenan received his [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge)|Master of Arts]] in Biology from the [[University of Oxford]] in 1940 and began to work at the [[Imperial Forestry Institute]] (now the [[Oxford Forestry Institute]])<ref>[http://www.plants.ox.ac.uk/ofi/ Oxford Forestry Institute<!-- bot-generated title -->] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302170136/http://www.plants.ox.ac.uk/ofi/ |date=2 March 2015 }} at www.plants.ox.ac.uk</ref> in [[Oxford]]. He collected plants from 1947 to 1948 in what is today [[Zambia]] and [[Tanzania]].\n\nHe began work at the [[herbarium]] of the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] in 1948 and became head of its African section in 1959. He became a member of the [[Linnean Society of London]] in 1952. In 1965, he became head of the herbarium and assistant director and became director of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew in 1976. He was a member of several [[learned society|learned societies]], and was president of the [[Association of Tropical Botany]] from 1970 to 1971, and of the [[Botanical Society of the British Isles]] in 1982. This botanist is denoted by the [[List of botanists by author abbreviation|author abbreviation]] '''<span class=\"vcard\"><span class=\"fn n\"><span class=\"nickname\">Brenan</span></span></span>''' when [[Author citation (botany)|citing]] a [[botanical name]].<ref>{{cite book|last = Brummitt|first = R. K.|author2=Powell, C. E.|title = Authors of Plant Names |publisher = [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] |year = 1992 |isbn = 978-1-84246-085-6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Ray Desmond (1994). ''Dictionary of British and Irish Botanists and Horticulturists including Plant Collectors, Flower Painters and Garden Designers''. Taylor & Francis and the [[Natural History Museum, London]]. {{ISBN|0-85066-843-3}}\n\n{{Directors of Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brenan, John Patrick Micklethwait}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British botanists]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in Kew Gardens]]\n[[Category:Botanists with author abbreviations]]\n[[Category:Burials at St. Anne's Church, Kew]]\n[[Category:English botanists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:People from Chislehurst]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n\n{{UK-botanist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:Reordered cats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Patrick_Micklethwait_Brenan"}
{"title_page": "Fort Grey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n[[File:Fort Grey.jpg|thumb|Fort Grey]]\n\n'''Fort Grey''', colloquially known as the \"cup and saucer\", is a [[Martello tower]] located on a tidal rock in Rocquaine Bay in [[Saint Peter, Guernsey]] on the west coast of the island.\n\n== Ch\u00e2teau de Rocquaine ==\nThe [[French language|French]] name of the rock is the ''Ch\u00e2teau de Rocquaine'' (Castle of Rocquaine); in [[Guern\u00e9siais]] ''Ch\u00e2t\u00e9 d\u00e9 Rocquo\u00efne'' probably built in the late medieval era, there was a small fort, referred to in the 1620s as used by the militia, not being in a fit state to withstand assault. In the 16th century the site of local [[witches]]' [[Witches' Sabbath|Sabbaths]]<ref name=\"JMBB\">{{cite book |first=James |last=Marr |title=Bailiwick Bastions |publisher=Guernsey Press |ISBN=0 902550 11 X}}</ref>{{rp|39}} and in 1617 there was reported a meeting between a local girl, Isabel Becquet and the devil.<ref>{{cite book |first=Montague |last=Summers |title=The history of witchcraft and demonology |publisher=Citadel (January 1, 1993) |ISBN=978-0806514529 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofwitchcr00summ_0 }}</ref> Marie de Callais from St Martin, was also convicted for belonging to the coven and burnt at the stake on 17 October 1617.<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite book |last=Strappini |first=Richard |title=St Martin, Guernsey, Channel Islands, a parish history from 1204 |date=2004}}</ref>{{rp|8}}\n\n== Fort Grey ==\nThe existing fort was built on the remnants of the old Chateau. Its white tower was originally built as a defence by the [[United Kingdom|British]] in 1804 during the [[Napoleonic Wars]], the builder was a local man, Thomas Henry from Clos du Valle<ref>{{cite book |first=R.A. |last=Henry |title=The Reclamation of the Braye du Valle 1806-2006}}</ref> The fort was named after [[Charles Grey, 1st Earl Grey]], who was [[Governor of Guernsey]] from 1797 to 1807.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Cahoon |url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Guernsey.html |title=Guernsey |publisher=Worldstatesmen.org |date= |accessdate=2013-01-13}}</ref><ref name=\"guernsey1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.museums.gov.gg/forthistory |title=Fort Grey |publisher=Guernsey Museums}}</ref> It was made one of three locations in the island where a warning gun would be fired in case of invasion.<ref name=JMBB/>\n\n[[File:Monument MV Prosperity Guernsey.jpg|thumb|Monument to the loss of {{MV|Prosperity||6}} on the night of 16/17 January 1974]]\n\nThe Fort Grey tower, like the other two Guernsey Martello towers, [[Fort Saumarez]] and [[Fort Hommet]], was intended as a [[keep]] for the battery in which it was placed. The Guernsey Martellos are smaller than the British towers, with the Fort Saumarez and Fort Hommet towers being smaller than the Fort Grey tower.{{#tag:ref|Forts Hommet and Saumarez have a diameter of 34 feet and stand 17 feet; Fort Grey has a diameter 36 feet and stands 26 feet high.<ref>Clements (1999), p.169.</ref>|group=Note}} Each mounted a 24-pounder [[carronade]] on the roof to protect the battery. Fort Saumarez and Fort Hommet also have exterior staircases up to the second floor.<ref name=Clements>Clements (1999), p. 87.</ref>\n\nThe connection between St Peter Port and the fort were improved with an upgrade of the road to military standard around 1808, using money arising from the sale of land from the reclaimed [[Braye du Valle, Guernsey|Braye du Valle]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Strappini |first=Richard |title=St Martin, Guernsey, Channel Islands, a parish history from 1204 |date=2004 |page=115}}</ref>\n\n== WW2 ==\n\nThe [[War Office]] in [[London]] sold Fort Grey to the [[States of Guernsey]] in 1891 for \u00a3185. During the [[German occupation of the Channel Islands]] in [[World War II]], the Germans [[Military occupation|occupied]] the fort, as they did most of the other fortifications in Guernsey.<ref name=\"guernsey1\"/> The fort was given the name ''Widerstandsnest Graur Turm'' (resistance nest Gray Tower) armed with a mobile [[3.7 cm Pak 36]] anti tank gun and machine guns.<ref>{{cite book |first=Ernie |last=Gavey |title=German Fortifications of Guernsey |publisher=Guernsey Armouries |ISBN=978-0953163106}}</ref>{{rp|37}}\n\n== Museum ==\n[[File:Guernsey 2011 149, Fort Grey info board.jpg|thumb|right|Museum sign]]\nMore recently Fort Grey has been adapted for other more peaceful uses and now operates as a local [[shipwreck]] [[museum]], housing a number of items of [[marine salvage]] from famous [[wrecks]], including the {{MV|Prosperity||6}} and ''Elwood Mead''. The items also include a cannon from {{HMS|Boreas|1806|6}} that points towards the nearby [[Les Hanois|Hanois]] rocks where ''Boreas'' sank in 1807 with the loss of her captain, at least half her crew, and possibly the captain's wife. An additional exhibit of the timbers from a 3rd-century Roman ship, nicknamed \"Asterix\", found in St Peter Port harbour in 1982 will shortly be on display close by, having taken decades to preserve the 1,700 year old timbers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/news/channel/update/2015-05-15/guernseys-roman-ship-moves-to-fort-grey/ |title=Guernsey\u2019s Roman ship moves to Fort Grey |publisher=ITV |date=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Protection==\nThe whole of Fort Grey and the slipway at Rocquaine was listed as a '''Protected Monument''' on 26 March 1938, reference PM238.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://planningexplorer.gov.gg/portal/servlets/LBSearchServlet?PKID=6340 |title=PM238 |publisher=States Of Guernsey}}</ref>\n\n== See also==\n*\n\n==Footnotes==\n; Citations\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n; Notes\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n* Clements, William H. (1998). ''Towers of Strength: Martello Towers Worldwide''. London: Pen & Sword. {{ISBN|978-0-85052-679-0}}.\n* Dillon, Paddy (2011). ''Channel Island Walks''. Cicerone Guide. {{ISBN|1-85284-288-1}}.\n* Grimsley, E. J. (1988). ''The historical development of the Martello Tower in the Channel Islands''. Sarnian Publications. {{ISBN|978-0951386804}}.\n\n==External links==\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20040808105930/http://www.museum.guernsey.net/fortgrey.htm Fort Grey], Museums, Guernsey\n* [http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Guernsey.html Governors of Guernsey]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120415011226/http://www.museum.guernsey.net/download/Marie%20de%20Garis%20parish%20history%20extracts%20-%20SPDB.pdf History of St. Pierre du Bois by Marie de Garis 1995] [[PDF]]\n\n{{coord|49|26|21|N|2|39|17|W|display=title|type:landmark_source:GNS-enwiki}}{{Castles in Guernsey}}\n[[Category:Castles in Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Fortifications in Guernsey|G]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure completed in 1804]]\n[[Category:Maritime museums]]\n[[Category:Martello towers]]\n[[Category:Museums in Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Towers completed in 1804]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n[[File:Fort Grey.jpg|thumb|Fort Grey]]\n\n'''Fort Grey''', colloquially known as the \"cup and saucer\", it is actually an [[Martello tower]] located on a tidal rock in Rocquaine Bay in [[Saint Peter, Guernsey]] located to the west of the island it has stunning views and a great place to watch the sunset.\n\n== Ch\u00e2teau de Rocquaine ==\nThe [[French language|French]] name of the rock is the ''Ch\u00e2teau de Rocquaine'' (Castle of Rocquaine); in [[Guern\u00e9siais]] ''Ch\u00e2t\u00e9 d\u00e9 Rocquo\u00efne'' probably built in the late medieval era, there was a small fort, referred to in the 1620s as used by the militia, not being in a fit state to withstand assault. In the 16th century the site of local [[witches]]' [[Witches' Sabbath|Sabbaths]]<ref name=\"JMBB\">{{cite book |first=James |last=Marr |title=Bailiwick Bastions |publisher=Guernsey Press |ISBN=0 902550 11 X}}</ref>{{rp|39}} and in 1617 there was reported a meeting between a local girl, Isabel Becquet and the devil.<ref>{{cite book |first=Montague |last=Summers |title=The history of witchcraft and demonology |publisher=Citadel (January 1, 1993) |ISBN=978-0806514529 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofwitchcr00summ_0 }}</ref> Marie de Callais from St Martin, was also convicted for belonging to the coven and burnt at the stake on 17 October 1617.<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite book |last=Strappini |first=Richard |title=St Martin, Guernsey, Channel Islands, a parish history from 1204 |date=2004}}</ref>{{rp|8}}\n\n== Fort Grey ==\nThe existing fort was built on the remnants of the old Chateau. Its white tower was originally built as a defence by the [[United Kingdom|British]] in 1804 during the [[Napoleonic Wars]], the builder was a local man, Thomas Henry from Clos du Valle<ref>{{cite book |first=R.A. |last=Henry |title=The Reclamation of the Braye du Valle 1806-2006}}</ref> The fort was named after [[Charles Grey, 1st Earl Grey]], who was [[Governor of Guernsey]] from 1797 to 1807.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ben Cahoon |url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Guernsey.html |title=Guernsey |publisher=Worldstatesmen.org |date= |accessdate=2013-01-13}}</ref><ref name=\"guernsey1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.museums.gov.gg/forthistory |title=Fort Grey |publisher=Guernsey Museums}}</ref> It was made one of three locations in the island where a warning gun would be fired in case of invasion.<ref name=JMBB/>\n\n[[File:Monument MV Prosperity Guernsey.jpg|thumb|Monument to the loss of {{MV|Prosperity||6}} on the night of 16/17 January 1974]]\n\nThe Fort Grey tower, like the other two Guernsey Martello towers, [[Fort Saumarez]] and [[Fort Hommet]], was intended as a [[keep]] for the battery in which it was placed. The Guernsey Martellos are smaller than the British towers, with the Fort Saumarez and Fort Hommet towers being smaller than the Fort Grey tower.{{#tag:ref|Forts Hommet and Saumarez have a diameter of 34 feet and stand 17 feet; Fort Grey has a diameter 36 feet and stands 26 feet high.<ref>Clements (1999), p.169.</ref>|group=Note}} Each mounted a 24-pounder [[carronade]] on the roof to protect the battery. Fort Saumarez and Fort Hommet also have exterior staircases up to the second floor.<ref name=Clements>Clements (1999), p. 87.</ref>\n\nThe connection between St Peter Port and the fort were improved with an upgrade of the road to military standard around 1808, using money arising from the sale of land from the reclaimed [[Braye du Valle, Guernsey|Braye du Valle]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Strappini |first=Richard |title=St Martin, Guernsey, Channel Islands, a parish history from 1204 |date=2004 |page=115}}</ref>\n\n== WW2 ==\n\nThe [[War Office]] in [[London]] sold Fort Grey to the [[States of Guernsey]] in 1891 for \u00a3185. During the [[German occupation of the Channel Islands]] in [[World War II]], the Germans [[Military occupation|occupied]] the fort, as they did most of the other fortifications in Guernsey.<ref name=\"guernsey1\"/> The fort was given the name ''Widerstandsnest Graur Turm'' (resistance nest Gray Tower) armed with a mobile [[3.7 cm Pak 36]] anti tank gun and machine guns.<ref>{{cite book |first=Ernie |last=Gavey |title=German Fortifications of Guernsey |publisher=Guernsey Armouries |ISBN=978-0953163106}}</ref>{{rp|37}}\n\n== Museum ==\n[[File:Guernsey 2011 149, Fort Grey info board.jpg|thumb|right|Museum sign]]\nMore recently Fort Grey has been adapted for other more peaceful uses and now operates as a local [[shipwreck]] [[museum]], housing a number of items of [[marine salvage]] from famous [[wrecks]], including the {{MV|Prosperity||6}} and ''Elwood Mead''. The items also include a cannon from {{HMS|Boreas|1806|6}} that points towards the nearby [[Les Hanois|Hanois]] rocks where ''Boreas'' sank in 1807 with the loss of her captain, at least half her crew, and possibly the captain's wife. An additional exhibit of the timbers from a 3rd-century Roman ship, nicknamed \"Asterix\", found in St Peter Port harbour in 1982 will shortly be on display close by, having taken decades to preserve the 1,700 year old timbers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/news/channel/update/2015-05-15/guernseys-roman-ship-moves-to-fort-grey/ |title=Guernsey\u2019s Roman ship moves to Fort Grey |publisher=ITV |date=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Protection==\nThe whole of Fort Grey and the slipway at Rocquaine was listed as a '''Protected Monument''' on 26 March 1938, reference PM238.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://planningexplorer.gov.gg/portal/servlets/LBSearchServlet?PKID=6340 |title=PM238 |publisher=States Of Guernsey}}</ref>\n\n== See also==\n*\n\n==Footnotes==\n; Citations\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n; Notes\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n* Clements, William H. (1998). ''Towers of Strength: Martello Towers Worldwide''. London: Pen & Sword. {{ISBN|978-0-85052-679-0}}.\n* Dillon, Paddy (2011). ''Channel Island Walks''. Cicerone Guide. {{ISBN|1-85284-288-1}}.\n* Grimsley, E. J. (1988). ''The historical development of the Martello Tower in the Channel Islands''. Sarnian Publications. {{ISBN|978-0951386804}}.\n\n==External links==\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20040808105930/http://www.museum.guernsey.net/fortgrey.htm Fort Grey], Museums, Guernsey\n* [http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Guernsey.html Governors of Guernsey]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120415011226/http://www.museum.guernsey.net/download/Marie%20de%20Garis%20parish%20history%20extracts%20-%20SPDB.pdf History of St. Pierre du Bois by Marie de Garis 1995] [[PDF]]\n\n{{coord|49|26|21|N|2|39|17|W|display=title|type:landmark_source:GNS-enwiki}}{{Castles in Guernsey}}\n[[Category:Castles in Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Fortifications in Guernsey|G]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure completed in 1804]]\n[[Category:Maritime museums]]\n[[Category:Martello towers]]\n[[Category:Museums in Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Towers completed in 1804]]\n", "name_user": "Formulaonewiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_Grey"}
{"title_page": "Waqar Zaka", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani television host, editor, actor, VJ, concept writer, director, producer}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Waqar Zaka\n| nationality   = Pakistani\n| alma_mater    =\n| birth_place   = [[Sargodha]], [[Pakistan]]\n| occupation    = [[Television host]]\n| years_active  = 2005\u2013present\n| known_for     = [[Living on the Edge (Sabse Himmat Wala Kon?)|Living on the Edge]]<br>[[Champions Hosted By Waqar Zaka|Champions]]\n|website = http://waqarzaka.net\n}}\n\n'''Waqar Zaka''' is a Pakistani [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]]-turned-television host.<ref name=\"tribune/14feb2013\">{{cite news|title=I am giving Pakistanis a platform to vent their frustrations: Waqar Zaka - The Express Tribune|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/507331/i-am-giving-pakistanis-a-platform-to-vent-their-frustrations-waqar-zaka/|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=The Express Tribune|date=14 February 2013}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nZaka claims to have done engineering from [[NED University of Engineering & Technology]].\n\nWaqar began his career during his school life by releasing the student song ''Nahi Parha Meine Poora Saal'' and then became a [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]]. After earning fame as VJ, he started hosting a TV [[reality show]] [[Living on the Edge: Sabse Himmat Wala Kon?|Living on the Edge]].<ref name=\"dawnnews/28may2019\">{{cite news |last1=\u0688\u06cc\u0633\u06a9 |first1=\u0627\u0646\u0679\u0631\u0679\u06cc\u0646\u0645\u0646\u0679 |title=\u0648\u0642\u0627\u0631 \u0630\u06a9\u0627 \u0646\u0648\u062c\u0648\u0627\u0646\u0648\u06ba \u06a9\u0648 \u0628\u06be\u0679\u06a9\u0627\u0646\u06d2 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0627 \u0645\u0648\u0627\u062f \u062a\u06cc\u0627\u0631 \u06a9\u0631\u0646\u06d2 \u067e\u0631 \u0634\u0631\u0645\u0646\u062f\u06c1 |url=https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1104219 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Dawn News Television |date=28 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"dawn/7march2009\">{{cite news|title=Chit chat Meet Waqar Zaka|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/448557/chit-chat-meet-waqar-zaka|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=DAWN.COM|date=7 March 2009|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"tribune/14feb2013\" /> Waqar then created and hosted [[reality shows]] ''XPOSED'',<ref name=\"dawn/7march2009\" /> ''King of Street Magic'',<ref name=\"dawn/7march2009\" /> ''Desi Kudiyan'' and ''The Cricket Challenge'' aired on [[ARY Musik]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/879155/i-am-the-reason-why-some-people-now-rule-the-entertainment-industry-waqar-zaka/|title=I am the reason why some people now rule the entertainment industry: Waqar Zaka|work=The Express Tribune|first=Sameen|last=Hassan|accessdate=22 June 2015|date=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 Pakistani general election]], Zaka ran for the seat of the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] from [[Constituency NA-253|Karachi NA-253]] constituency,<ref>{{cite news|title=Waqar Zaka says 'Line Pe Ajao' - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/837229/waqar-zaka-says-line-pe-ajao/|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=The Express Tribune|date=12 February 2015}}</ref> but was unsuccessful<ref name=\"dawnnews/28may2019\" /> and secured only 31 votes out of the 211,768 total votes cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Downloads/General%20Election%202013/Detailed%20Gazzette/Notification%20-%20National%20Assembly.pdf|title=Election Commission of Pakistan Notification|work=Election Commission of Pakistan|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> Zaka claims he ran to demonstrate how to run for election for his show ''Main Banoonga Minister''; he stated that this was \"the only entertaining way of telling our youth how to be a part of the system\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahmood |first1=Rafay |title=I am giving Pakistanis a platform to vent their frustrations: Waqar Zaka |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/507331/i-am-giving-pakistanis-a-platform-to-vent-their-frustrations-waqar-zaka/ |accessdate=22 August 2019 |work=The Express Tribune |date=14 February 2013 |language=en}}</ref> He ran on a platform of prioritizing and improving access to entertainment and the internet.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/529514/waqar-zaka-hopes-to-go-from-cobra-to-constituency/|title=Waqar Zaka hopes to go from cobra to constituency - The Express Tribune|date=1 April 2013|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aaj.tv/2013/04/main-banoonga-minister-waqar-zaka-strives-to-contest-elections/|title=Main Banoonga Minister: Waqar Zaka strives to contest elections|last=Ishtiaque|first=Aqsa|work=Aaj News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128123043/https://www.aaj.tv/2013/04/main-banoonga-minister-waqar-zaka-strives-to-contest-elections/|access-date=5 June 2018|archive-date=28 November 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, he announced a political movement in Pakistan called Tehreek-e-Tech.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mangobaaz.com/waqar-zaka-just-launched-his-own-political-party-and-i-cant-believe-i-actually-kinda-agree-with-him | title=Waqar Zaka Just Launched His Own Political Party And I Can't Believe I Actually Kinda Agree With Him | https://www.mangobaaz.com/waqar-zaka-just-launched-his-own-political-party-and-i-cant-believe-i-actually-kinda-agree-with-him | accessdate=9 April 2019| archive-date=9 April 2019 }}</ref> In May 2019, he apologized to the people for destroying the young minds during his TV reality show ''Living on the Edge''.<ref name=\"dawnnews/28may2019\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka seeks apology from nation for destroying young minds |url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Entertainment/493945-Waqar-Zaka-seeks-apology-nation-destroying-young-minds/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Dunya News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530064649/http://dunyanews.tv/en/Entertainment/493945-Waqar-Zaka-seeks-apology-nation-destroying-young-minds/ |archive-date=30 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Champions With Waqar Zaka==\nIn November 2019, Zaka began hosting a TV reality show ''[[Champions (Pakistani TV series)|Champions With Waqar Zaka]]'' on [[BOL Network]].<ref name=\"pakistantoday/10april2020\" /> In January 2020, the TV show ''Champions With Waqar Zaka'' was banned by [[Pakistan Electronic Media Regulatory Authority]] (PEMRA)<ref name=\"pakistantoday/10april2020\">{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka's show 'Champions' to remain suspended, IHC rules - Pakistan Today |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/04/10/waqar-zakas-show-champions-remain-suspended-ihc-rules/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> for being \"offensive towards social, religious and cultural values of this country\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka's Show Champions Gets Banned By PEMRA |url=https://propakistani.pk/lens/waqar-zakas-show-champions-gets-banned-by-pemra/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Lens |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> In April 2020, the [[Islamabad High Court]] upheld the decision of PEMRA to ban ''Champions With Waqar Zaka''. <ref>{{cite news |last1=\u0688\u06cc\u0633\u06a9 |first1=\u0648\u06cc\u0628 |title=\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0636 \u0645\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0646\u0634\u0631 \u06a9\u0631\u0646\u06d2 \u067e\u0631 \u0628\u0648\u0644 \u0679\u06cc \u0648\u06cc \u06a9\u06d2 \u067e\u0631\u0648\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0686\u06cc\u0645\u067e\u06cc\u0626\u0646\u0632 \u067e\u0631 \u067e\u0627\u0628\u0646\u062f\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0631 |url=https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1125800 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Dawn News Television |date=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the suspension of his TV reality show ''[[Champions (Pakistani TV series)|Champions With Waqar Zaka]]'', he began hosting a late night show on YouTube called ''Headphone Show''. The show was  criticised for \"constant swearing\" and \"inappropriate conversations\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Lewd headphone show designed to help audience, insists Waqar Zaka {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/entertainment/2020/04/lewd-headphone-show-designed-to-help-audience-insists-waqar-zaka/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Samaa TV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413074930/https://www.samaa.tv/entertainment/2020/04/lewd-headphone-show-designed-to-help-audience-insists-waqar-zaka/ |archive-date=13 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2017, he received an award from [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]] for his social and humanitarian work in the war-torn areas of Syria and Myanmar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Waqar Zaka receives award from Dr Abdul Qadeer Khan|url=http://nation.com.pk/snippets/31-Mar-2017/waqar-zaka-receives-award-for-his-humanitarian-services|accessdate=8 July 2017|work=The Nation}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn January 2017, a video went viral on social media websites where Zaka was severely assaulted by a group of people in Karachi. Zaka was injured in the attack,<ref>{{cite news |title=TV anchor Waqar Zaka thrashed by unidentified man in Karachi - Entertainment - Dunya News |url=https://dunyanews.tv/en/Entertainment/372645-TV-anchor-Waqar-Zaka-thrashed-by-unidentified-man- |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=dunyanews.tv}}</ref> leaving his hand fractured.<ref>{{cite news |title=TV host Waqar Zaka assaulted {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2017/01/tv-host-waqar-zaka-assaulted/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Samaa TV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=TV host Waqar Zaka assaulted in Karachi - Pakistan Today |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2017/01/28/tv-host-waqar-zaka-assaulted-in-karachi/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk}}</ref> Zaka later reconciled with his attacker.<ref>{{cite news |title=Drop scene: Waqar Zaka comes to terms with attacker {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/culture/2017/02/drop-scene-waqar-zaka-comes-to-terms-with-attacker/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Samaa TV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka takes a \u0091U-turn\u0092 |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/30562/waqar-zaka-takes-a-u-turn/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Daily Times |date=6 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, media reported that Zaka was arrested by police in Karachi for possessing alcohol,<ref>{{cite news |title=Arrested for possession of sheesha not alcohol, Waqar Zaka clarifies |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/396309-arrese |accessdate=28 January 2019 |work=www.thenews.com.pk |language=en}}</ref> however Zaka clarified that he was charged with possession of [[Hookah|sheesha]] instead of alcohol.<ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka arrested, denies possessing alcohol |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1850448/4-waqar-zaka-arrested-denies-possessing-alcohol/ |accessdate=28 January 2019 |work=The Express Tribune |date=19 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka lashes out at media for reporting he was arrested for alcohol possession - Pakistan Today |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/11/19/waqar-zaka-lashes-out-at-media-for-reporting-he-was-arrested-for-alcohol-possession/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|6680650}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zaka, Waqar}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:VJs (media personalities)]]\n[[Category:Pakistani television hosts]]\n[[Category:People from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Pakistani stunt performers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Sargodha]]\n[[Category:NED University of Engineering and Technology alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani television host, editor, actor, VJ, concept writer, director, producer}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Waqar Zaka\n| nationality   = Pakistani\n| alma_mater    =\n| birth