rnath Sharma, Sushil Choudhary, and Priti Sahani\n** ''[[Padmaavat]]'' - [[SLB Films]] and [[Viacom 18 Motion Pictures]] - [[Sanjay Leela Bhansali]], Sudhanshu Vats, and Ajit Andhare\n** ''[[Sanju]]'' - [[Rajkumar Hirani Films]] and [[Vinod Chopra Films]] - [[Rajkumar Hirani]] and [[Vidhu Vinod Chopra]]\n** ''[[Stree (2018 film)#Cast|Stree]]'' - [[Maddock Films]], and D2R Films - \t[[Dinesh Vijan]], Raj Nidimoru and Krishna D.K.\n\n===2020s===\n* '''2020 ''[KABIR SINGH]\nSANDEEP VANGA REDDY\n** ''[[Chhichhore]]'' \u2013 [[Nadiadwala Grandson Entertainment]] \u2013 [[Sajid Nadiadwala]]\n** ''[[Mission Mangal]]'' - Cape of Good Films, [[Hope Productions]] and [[Fox Star Studios]] - Aruna Bhatia and Anil Naidu\n** ''[[Uri: The Surgical Strike]]'' - [[RSVP Movies]] - [[Ronnie Screwvala]]\n** ''[[War (2019 film)|War]]'' - [[Yash Raj Films]] - [[Aditya Chopra]]\n\n==Special 50 Year Award==\n\nIn 2005, [[Filmfare]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmfare.com/|title=Bollywood News, Filmfare Awards, Movie Reviews, Celebrity Photos & Updates|website=filmfare.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref> announced the best movie of the last 50 years as ''[[Sholay]]'', although the film did not win the [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare Award]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards/winners|title=Filmfare Awards Winners From 1953 to 2018|website=filmfare.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref> for Best Film in its year of release.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Movie]]\n* [[Filmfare Awards]]\n* [[Bollywood]]\n* [[Cinema of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards/winners Filmfare Awards Best Film]\n\n{{Filmfare Awards}}\n{{Filmfare Award for Best Film}}\n\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards|F]]\n[[Category:Awards for best film]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name = [[Filmfare Awards|Filmfare Award]] for Best Film \n| image =  \n| caption = [[Raazi]]   is the current winner of this award \n| description = Best Film\n| presenter = ''[[Filmfare]]''\n| country = India\n| year = ''[[Do Bigha Zamin]]'' ([[1st Filmfare Awards|1954]])\n| holder = ''[[Gully Boy]]'' ([[65th Filmfare Awards|2020]])\n| website = [http://filmfareawards.indiatimes.com/ Filmfare Awards]\n}}\n\nThe '''Filmfare Award for Best Film''' is given by the ''[[Filmfare]]'' magazine as part of its annual [[Filmfare Awards]] for [[Hindi film]]s.\n\nThe award was first given in 1954. Here is a list of the award winners and the nominees of the respective years. Each individual entry shows the title followed by the production company, and the producer.<br>\n[[Yash Raj Films]] has produced 18 films that have been nominated, the most for any production house. It also shares the most wins at 4 along with ''Bimal Roy Productions'' and [[UTV Motion Pictures]]. While [[Yash Chopra]] has been the producer of most of the nominated and all the winning films of Yash Raj Films, [[Bimal Roy]] has been the producer of the all the nominated films of Bimal Roy Productions, thus making them the producer with the most wins. Bimal Roy, Yash Chopra and [[Sanjay Leela Bhansali]] have each directed 4 winning films, the most for any director. [[Aamir Khan]] has starred in 9 winning films which is the most for any actor in a leading role.\n\n==Winners and nominees==\n\n===1950s===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#bebebe\"\n! width=\"5%\" | Year\n! width=\"40%\" | Film\n! width=\"55%\" | Studio(s)\n|-\n| rowspan=3 style=\"text-align:center\" | '''1954'''<br /><small>[[1st Filmfare Awards|(1st)]]</small>\n|- style=\"background:#FAEB86\" \n| '''''[[Do Bigha Zamin]]'''''\n| '''[[Bimal Roy|Bimal Roy Productions]]'''\n|-\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center\" | '''No Other Nominees'''\n|-\n| rowspan=3 style=\"text-align:center\" | '''1955'''<br /><